 existing merged context issues, especially regarding AOT processing and generated files. I'm thinking about the implications for features like CGLIB and how those settings might affect the AOT generator. The setup using @Bean methods could lead to some failures if configurations are missing. Additionally, there's a need to consider naming and static methods in this context.\"},{\"type\":\"summary_text\",\"text\":\"**Reviewing TestContextAotGenerator**\\n\\nI'm considering how TestContextAotGenerator.processAheadOfTime might utilize caching with a unique class, needing to reset before building. However, if another test has run on the same class, it could cause problems. I think it’s worth examining if making a @TestBean field package-private in a static nested test class is beneficial. I’m also curious whether the AOT generator could instantiate the context, especially regarding the BeanOverrideTestExecutionListener. It’s important to inspect the process to confirm if it invokes the post-processor correctly.\"}]}"}, {"type": "toolCall", "id": "call_ZaYN1U4a3rOSQnyDoSxQwmiL|fc_04fbef9b7139a29e016a284d916fb081949ab314fd2e67ce73", "name": "read", "arguments": {"path": "/home/vjovanov/c/forge/forge1/graalvm-reachability-metadata/forge/local_repositories/source_context/org.springframework/spring-test/7.0.0/main/extracted/org/springframework/test/context/aot/TestContextAotGenerator.java", "offset": 150, "limit": 180}}], "api": "openai-responses", "provider": "OCA", "model": "oca/gpt-5.5", "usage": {"input": 1258, "output": 1086, "cacheRead": 54272, "cacheWrite": 0, "totalTokens": 56616, "cost": {"input": 0, "output": 0, "cacheRead": 0, "cacheWrite": 0, "total": 0}}, "stopReason": "toolUse", "timestamp": 1781026165477, "responseId": "resp_04fbef9b7139a29e016a284d765bd4819487782eda63f2c438"}}
